I am not sure I agree with the suggestion that junior QS was intended to 
be the default alphabet with senior QS for handwriting alone.  I think 
of junior as being for beginners while they are still getting used to 
the alphabet.  I find that senior makes more distinctive word shapes, 
which are easier to remember without the necessity of &quot;sounding the 
letters out,&quot; i.e. sight recognition is improved, and it may even may 
make reading faster to those adept in senior.

I see the distinction between senior and junior as similar to that of 
printed T.O. and cursive T.O.  In the past, cursive was not practical to 
use for printed material so almost everything was printed in 
disconnected letters.  Cursive writing was reserved for handwriting.  
But that is no longer necessary.  Computer technology should be able to 
make the use of senior forms relatively easy, so why should we not use 
the senior form in material printed for proficient readers? 

It is my understanding that Arabic letters change their shape depending 
on their location in a word without causing distress to Arabic readers.  
Should not QS have the flexibility to use the senior forms in printed 
material if the writer prefers it?  The senior forms are  more fluid and 
aesthetically appealing to me than the junior version of the alphabet.

Paige

